ool to promote Jewish pride. He discusses Kahane’s theory of violence as a mechanism to assure Jewish safety, and traces how his Zionism evolved from a fervent support of Israel to a belief that the Zionist project had failed. Magid examines how tradition and classical Jewish texts profoundly influenced Kahane’s thought later in life, and argues that Kahane’s enduring legacy lies not in his Israeli career but in the challenge he posed to the liberalism and assimilatory project of the postwar American Jewish establishment.This incisive book shows how Kahane was a quintessentially American figure, one who adopted the radicalism of the militant Left as a tenet of Jewish survival.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aPolitical activistszIsraelvBiography. 0aPolitical activistszNew York (State)zNew YorkvBiography. 0aRabbiszIsraelvBiography. 0aRabbiszNew York (State)zNew YorkvBiography 0aRabbiszNew York (State)zNew YorkvBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Political.2bisacsh1 aMagid, Shaul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073912140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978069121266140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691212661423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691212661/original  a978-3-11-073912-1  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK